<article>
  <h2>unsafeHTML &amp; Trusted Types: An Interactive Demo</h2>

  <p>
    This site demonstrates a security gap in Lit's <code>unsafeHTML</code> directive:
    it silently bypasses the browser's <strong>Trusted Types</strong> enforcement via
    Lit's internal <code>'lit-html'</code> policy — a no-op identity function that
    blesses any string as safe HTML.
  </p>

  <p>
    The demos walk through the problem step by step and present a proposed fix.
    Open DevTools to see what's happening in each demo.
  </p>

  <h3>The 6-Page Narrative</h3>
  <ol>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/1-xss-risk/' | url }}"><strong>The XSS Risk</strong></a> — unsafeHTML with raw user input fires an alert.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/2-manual-sanitization/' | url }}"><strong>Manual Sanitization Helps (But Isn't Enforced)</strong></a> — DOMPurify stops the XSS, but nothing enforces its use.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/3-trusted-types-bypass/' | url }}"><strong>Trusted Types Doesn't Help (Today)</strong></a> — Even with TT active, Lit's internal policy blesses the XSS string.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/4-trusted-html-breaks/' | url }}"><strong>TrustedHTML Breaks Current unsafeHTML</strong></a> — Passing TrustedHTML to the existing directive throws an error.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/5-modified-directive/' | url }}"><strong>The Proposed Fix</strong></a> — A modified directive accepts TrustedHTML and inserts it safely.</li>
    <li><a href="{{ '/pages/6-future-sethtml/' | url }}"><strong>Future Direction: setHTML()</strong></a> — The upcoming Sanitizer API offers a safe sink without Trusted Types.</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Key Code Locations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>The no-op policy (the root cause):</strong><br>
      <code>lit-html.ts:263–267</code> — <code>trustedTypes.createPolicy('lit-html', { createHTML: (s) =&gt; s })</code>
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The original directive:</strong><br>
      <code>directives/unsafe-html.ts</code> — fake TemplateStringsArray path
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>The proposed fix:</strong><br>
      <code>directives/unsafe-html-tt.ts</code> — TrustedHTML path via <code>setHTMLUnsafe</code>
    </li>
  </ul>

